<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Please reply to:</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2.85pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Green Lanes Protection Group</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> – Further written evidence</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Deregulation Draft Bill ('the Bill')</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Summary of Purpose</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">GLPG</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> supports the proposals by the Peak District Green Lanes Alliance (PDGLA) to add provisions to the Bill. This note sets out the reasons which justify the amendments.</span><br /><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Those proposals in essence are:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">A</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> - To classify as restricted byways unsealed unclassified roads (UUCRs) as entered on the local authority's List of Streets (LoS),  subject to appropriate exceptions.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">[We suggest this could be inserted as </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">1</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">3A  Unrecorded rights of way: clarification</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">]</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">B</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> - To downgrade existing unsealed byways open to all traffic (BOATs) to restricted byway (RB) status.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">If necessary, provision B could be limited to unsealed BOATs in National Parks and Areas of Natural Beauty (AONBs) </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">[We suggest this could be inserted as </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">12A  Recorded rights: revision where unsealed</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">]</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Summary of Reasons</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 0.55pt; text-indent:-0.55pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 0.55pt; text-indent:-0.55pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">GLPG's own reasons for supporting the PDGLA proposals are these:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 0.55pt; text-indent:-0.55pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">R1.</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">  There is overwhelming evidence across the nation of damage to highways, of damage to the environment and of risk and nuisance to all other users caused by use of motor vehicles on unsealed ways in the countryside. The problem is acute in National Parks (also in AONBs), and particularly so in the Peak District which has outstanding landscape features and is a lung within the biggest body of population in the country.</span><br /><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">R2.</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">  Restraint of recreational motorised use in the countryside is in accord with Government policy (see 'Supplementary information' below).</span><br /><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">R3.</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">  The purpose of Clauses 12 - 18 of the Bill (see 'Legislation existing and proposed' below) is to correct loopholes in the rights of way system, in addition to the Bill's primary purposes of reducing red tape and demands on public resources. The PDGLA proposals meet all three objectives.</span><br /><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">R4.</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">  Lists of Streets are not records of public rights; they refer only to public maintenance liability.  The only practical way to ascertain what rights exist on ways on the LoS is by determination under s53 Wildlife and Countryside Act 1981 (the 1981 Act) which normally involves lengthy and expensive procedures.  By letter dated 28 Nov 2006 Defra confirmed this position and urged all surveying authorities to complete determinations ahead of the cut-off  of unrecorded rights of way in Jan 2026 (see 'Supplementary information' below).  PDGLA's proposals give immediate effect to Defra's objective.</span><br /><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">R5.  </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The combined effect of the Countryside and Rights of Way Act 2000 (CROWA) and the Natural Environment and Rural Communities Act 2006 (NERCA) is that unrecorded rights for mechanically propelled vehicles (MPVs) are not extinguished at the cut-off in 2026, unlike unrecorded bridleway and footpath rights. In the absence of a formal record of rights, it will not be practicable to bring prosecutions even where MPV rights do not exist.</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">  That means that off-roaders will be able to drive with impunity on UUCRs even though they have no right to be there. The PDGLA proposals remove that unjust anomaly.</span><br /><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">R6.  </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The proposals recognise the need to protect the "ordinary road network" (Defra's phrase).  Very few UUCRs (commonly known as "green lanes") can be so described, but such cases would be excluded.  So too would ways which are patently bridleways or footpaths.  Exception in such cases could be way of 'designation' by SAs as promoted in Clause 13 of the Bill.</span><br /><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">R7.  </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The fact that MPV rights may exist historically (generated by the wholly different and ancient use by horse and cart) is no reason to allow the needless desecration of green lanes by increasing recreational use in MPVs, including those run commercially and now being promoted on the internet. This is precisely the reason why the Government introduced NERCA, and why PDGLA extends its proposals to include existing unsealed BOATs. If that is considered to be too draconian (which the public would not) the alternative is to concentrate on situations where the problem is most acute (National Parks and AONBs).</span><br /><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">R8.</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">  Clarification of rights on UUCRs needs to include BOAT applications currently being processed, the determination of which should also be limited to RB status.  The precedent for this lies in s67(9) NERCA which limited to RB status applications allowed to be completed under s48(9) CROWA.</span><br /><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">R9.  </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Use of a "blanket" approach to rights on green lanes (and UUCRs in particular) is directly comparable to the reclassification of RUPPs under CROWA, the extinguishment of MPV rights under NERCA and the proposed cut-off of rights in 2026.  In each case, adequate safeguards were or will be built in to protect significant exceptions.</span><br /><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">R10.</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">  Classification of UUCRS as RBs would bring certainty to the rights over such ways long before the cut-off date.  RBs recorded in this way, together with unsealed BOAT s downgraded to RB status, would stand to be protected as such under Clause 12.  Given a recorded status, neither category would need to be designated under Clause 13.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">R11.</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">  There is no difficulty in using 'unsealed' as the criterion, as use can be made of the existing definition in s22BB(1)(b)(ii) Road Traffic Regulation Act 1984 (</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">"...whose surface, or most of whose surface, does not consist of concrete, tarmacadam, coated roadstone or other prescribed material"</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Supplementary information</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 0.55pt; text-indent:-0.55pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Government Policy</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 0.55pt; text-indent:-0.55pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 0.55pt; text-indent:-0.55pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">In November 2000 CROWA was enacted, in which s47 converted Roads Used as Public Paths (RUPPs) to Restricted Byways.  Under s53, rights of way generally (not including latent MPV rights) are to be extinguished if not recorded on the DMS at the cut-off date - provisionally 1 January 2026.  Commencement of both measures was or is delayed.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 0.55pt; text-indent:-0.55pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 0.55pt; text-indent:-0.55pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">In December 2003, the then Minister for Rural Affairs (Alun Michael) said:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“As Rural Affairs Minister, I have been approached by many individuals and organisations who are deeply concerned about problems caused by the use of mechanically propelled vehicles on rights of way and in the wider countryside. I share these concerns, having seen for myself examples of damage to fragile tracks and other aspects of our natural and cultural heritage in various areas of the country. There is considerable concern about behaviour that causes distress to others seeking quiet enjoyment of the countryside …</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">I do not think that it makes sense that historic evidence of use by horse drawn vehicles or dedications for vehicular use at a time before the internal combustion engine existed can give rise to rights to use modern mechanically propelled vehicles. Those who suffer from vehicle misuse find this incomprehensible and in this paper we offer new proposals that are intended to address what many have come to view as the inappropriate and unsustainable way in which vehicular rights are acquired and claimed on rights of way.”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Legislation - existing and proposed</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 0.55pt; text-indent:-0.55pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 0.55pt; text-indent:-0.55pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">In March 2006 NERCA became law accompanied by commencement of s47 CROWA. Essentially, NERCA extinguished unrecorded public rights for the use of MPVs, subject to a number of exceptions.  The majority of applications to establish MPV rights under those exceptions have now been resolved.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 0.55pt; text-indent:-0.55pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 0.55pt; text-indent:-0.55pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Government policy for many years has been to increase access to the countryside for all users other than MPVs.  In late 2008 the Stakeholders Working Group (SWG) was set up, its report - called 'Stepping Forward' - being published in March 2010.  The foreword speaks for itself (</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">emphasis added):</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 0.55pt; text-indent:-0.55pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">"</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">The incompleteness of the legal record of public rights of way has been a contentious</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">subject for many years.</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> The Countryside and Rights of Way Act 2000 sought to address this.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">It provided for a ‘cut-off date’ in 2026, so that unrecorded pre-1949 public rights of way</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">would cease to exist if not specifically preserved by regulations.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 0.55pt; text-indent:-0.55pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">This has brought into sharp relief the task of capturing on the definitive map and statement</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">before that date those currently unrecorded pre-1949 public routes that are already in use,</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">or are useful or potentially useful to the connectivity of the local rights of way network. It</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">was an inherent component of the Government’s policy in enacting the cut-off provision</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">that such routes should be preserved. </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">However, one major source of concern, for all</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">concerned, has been the complexity and long-windedness of the recording procedures</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">."</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 0.55pt; text-indent:-0.55pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 0.55pt; text-indent:-0.55pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">It is this report, together with consideration by Defra of other problems, that has led to Clauses 12 to 18, together with Schedule 6, of the current Draft Deregulation Bill.  These proposed measures seek to protect certain recorded rights of way, to protect private access in cases of extinguishment of public rights, to widen existing provisions relating to public path orders, to extend powers relating to gates and stiles, to widen measures for recovery of costs under public path orders, and (Sch 6, Part I) to modify procedures for ascertaining rights of way.  In short, the primary purpose of these clauses is to correct anomalies rather than achieve cuts in red tape and use of resources.  The PDGLA proposals do however serve all three purposes. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 0.55pt; text-indent:-0.55pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Outstanding problems</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 0.55pt; text-indent:-0.55pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 0.55pt; text-indent:-0.55pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Although NERCA has been very successful in implementing Government policy as to restricting MPVs in the countryside by ending new rights, this extends only to cases where lower rights are recorded on the definitive map and statement (DMS), or where the way in question is on neither the DMS </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">nor the LoS.  Major problems remain:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 0.55pt; text-indent:-0.55pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 0.55pt; text-indent:-0.55pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Ways in the category falling between Classified Roads and rights of way shown on the DMS are commonly known as Unclassified Roads (UCRs) although that term is no longer officially used.  For UCRs there is no system of recording rights other than the very lengthy, costly and uncertain process of reviewing the DMS by surveying authorities (SAs).  The average cost to the public purse of resolving opposed orders by public inquiry was calculated recently by Defra at over £15,000, and that is in addition to private costs of research, advice, representation and personal attendance.</span><br /><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 0.55pt; text-indent:-0.55pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Without that process, all rights over UCRs remain in limbo, the scale of the problem having been exacerbated by authorities who mistakenly believed that entry on the LoS obviated the need to record rights on the DMS.</span><br /><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 0.55pt; text-indent:-0.55pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Broadly speaking, UCRs fall into two categories: sealed roads (which are part of the 'ordinary road network') and 'green lanes'.  As a result of there being no record of rights on UCRs, there is extensive abuse of green lanes by recreational off-roaders who take advantage of the lack of legal clarity and who choose to interpret the public records as </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">presenting a right to use the ways in MPVs.  The problem is compounded by commercial interests, largely and increasingly aided by internet functions, promoting off-roading as a sport.  That is not only contrary to the policy introduced by Alun Michael in 2003; it also results in danger to all other users (particularly horse riders), destruction of surfaces to the point of making paths unusable by the disabled, walkers, horse riders, cyclists or horse drawn vehicles, and other damage to the environment in the form of noise and pollution.  In short, the tiny minority of recreational users in MPVs prevent the use and enjoyment of their rights by the majority. The damage also results in rapidly increasing costs to local authorities in fulfilling their responsibility to maintain and repair. A </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">badly-damaged BOAT or UCR can cost up to £75,000 per mile to repair.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 0.55pt; text-indent:-0.55pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 0.55pt; text-indent:-0.55pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The problem is particularly acute in sensitive areas such as National Parks and AONBs.  The Peak District is an outstanding example of the problem as it is also an outstanding example of the environmental heritage which the Government and countless others affected seek to preserve and enjoy. A poll by ICM commissioned in 2004 by the Ramblers produced a 94% response, of which 87% said that recreational off-roading should be banned in National Parks and AONBs. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 0.55pt; text-indent:-0.55pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 0.55pt; text-indent:-0.55pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The need to resolve what rights exist on UCRs was in focus in Defra's letter on 28 Nov 2006 referred to at R4 above.  It said: </span></li></ol><p style="margin:3.6pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">"Consequently, any route that on 1 January 2026 is shown on the list of streets but not on the definitive map will have any unrecorded [bridleway or footpath] rights extinguished, subject to the terms of the Countryside &amp; Rights of Way Act 2000.</span></p><p style="margin:3.6pt 0pt 0pt 0.55pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-0.55pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 3.7pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Local authorities are therefore urged to ensure that any unrecorded footpath, bridleway and restricted byway rights are recorded on the definitive map and statement by the cut-off date of 2026, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">regardless </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">of whether they are also shown on the list required to be kept under section 36(6) of the Highways Act 1980, the 'list of streets' ".</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 0.55pt; text-indent:-0.55pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 0.55pt; text-indent:-0.55pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">In an 'Impact Assessment' leading up to the Deregulation Bill signed on 4 May 2012 by the Minister, Richard Benyon, Defra said:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 0.55pt; text-indent:-0.55pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">"The processes for recording PRoW are complex, slow and resource intensive. This has hampered the recording of all pre1949 rights of way on the definitive map and statement by the deadline of 2026 set out in the Countryside and Rights of Way (CROW) Act 2000 and 2000 Rural White Paper. </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">Government intervention is required in order to simplify the legal/policy framework</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">." </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">(emphasis added).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 0.55pt; text-indent:-0.55pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The PDGLA proposals subscribe to that need. In the Peak District National Park alone, the numbers are large and the delay protracted.  In the last 6 years, 21 cases have been determined (but not necessarily finalised) and 80 applications are outstanding. This has necessitated extra staff.  No figures are available nationally.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 0.55pt; text-indent:-0.55pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The opportunity to rectify these problems</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 0.55pt; text-indent:-0.55pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 0.55pt; text-indent:-0.55pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The PDGLA proposals seek (a) to subscribe to Government policy as to the environment, the correction of anomalies, the reduction of red tape and the use of resources; (b) to protect the rights of the majority from disproportionate damage done by the tiny minority; and (c) to bring certainty to rights on UUCRs well before Jan 2026.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 0.55pt; text-indent:-0.55pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 0.55pt; text-indent:-0.55pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The Draft Deregulation Bill presents an outstanding opportunity to address these matters by way of extension to clauses 12 -18 and Schedule 6.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 0.55pt; text-indent:-0.55pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">21 August 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2.85pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">6</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2.85pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2.85pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> GLPG is an alliance of the organisations shown below.  Its purpose is to prevent an increase in motor veh</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">icular rights on green lanes</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2.85pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> The legal reasoning is explained in a note dated 20 June 2007 from John Riddall, joint author of  'Rights of Way - a Guide to Law and Practice', an authority heavily relied on by the Planning Inspectorate and all those involved in rights of way matters. The letter from Defra dated 28 Nov 2006 is badly worded on this point.</span></p></body></html>